    37	## Directory Layout
    38	
    39	```
    40	<name>/
    41	├── template.yaml          # Manifest (required)
    42	├── states.yaml            # State machine (optional)
    43	├── settings.json          # Template-shipped project settings (optional)
    44	├── plan.rhei.md           # Single-file plan skeleton
    45	│   ── OR ──
    46	├── index.rhei.md          # Directory-workspace index skeleton
    47	├── tasks/                 # Directory-workspace task skeletons
    48	│   ├── 01-step.md
    49	│   └── ...
    50	└── ...                    # Additional files (text rendered; binary copied)
    51	```
    52	
    53	A template must contain exactly one plan entry point: either `plan.rhei.md` (single-file) or `index.rhei.md` (directory workspace). Containing both is an error.
    54	
    55	## Manifest Schema (`template.yaml`)
    56	
    57	```yaml
    58	name: <identifier>             # Template identifier (must match directory name)
    59	version: <yaml-scalar>         # Template version (informational; displayed by `rhei templates`;
    60	                               #   no semantic-version validation in v1)
    61	description: <string>          # One-line human-readable summary
    62	
    63	inputs:
    64	  - name: <identifier>        # Variable name, referenced as {{name}} in skeletons
    65	    description: <string>      # What this input controls
    66	    type: <string|number|boolean|path|array|object>  # Value type (default: string)
    67	    required: <boolean>        # Whether the input must be supplied (default: true)
    68	    default: <value>           # Default value (makes the input optional; mutually
    69	                               #   exclusive with required: true)
    70	    positional: <integer>       # Optional 1-based positional CLI slot for short
    71	                               #   `rhei instantiate <template> <value>` input
    72	    validate: <regex>          # Optional regex the value must match
    73	    items:                     # Required for `type: array`
    74	      type: <...>
    75	      ...
    76	    properties:                # Optional for `type: object`
    77	      <property-name>:
    78	        type: <...>
    79	        required: <boolean>
    80	        default: <value>
    81	        ...
    82	```
    83	
    84	### Validation Rules
    85	
    86	- `name` must match the enclosing directory name.
    87	- `inputs[].name` values must be unique within the manifest.
    88	- `version` is informational metadata. In v1 it may be any YAML scalar and is not semantically validated.
    89	- An input with `required: true` (the default) must not declare a `default`.
    90	- An input with a `default` is implicitly `required: false`.
    91	- An input with `required: false` and no `default` resolves to the empty string when not supplied by the user. Templates are pure text substitution in v1, so authors should tolerate that empty string directly or prefer declaring a `default`.
    92	- `positional`, when present, must be a positive integer. Positional indexes must be unique within a manifest and contiguous starting at `1`.
    93	- `type: array` inputs must declare `items`.
    94	- `type: object` inputs may declare `properties`. Properties are required by default unless they declare either `required: false` or a `default`.
    95	- `validate` is only valid on scalar input types (`string`, `number`, `boolean`, `path`).
    96	- Optional inputs with no `default` resolve to type-shaped empty values:
    97	  - `string`, `path` → `""`
    98	  - `number`, `boolean` → `null`
    99	  - `array` → `[]`
   100	  - `object` → `{}`
   101	- For `type: array` and `type: object`, positional values, `KEY=VALUE`, `--set KEY=...`, and `--set-file KEY=...` values are parsed as YAML/JSON snippets before validation.
   102	- `type: path` values are rendered exactly as supplied by the user or manifest `default`; instantiation does not rewrite them to absolute paths. Relative `path` values are interpreted relative to the instantiating process `cwd` only when the CLI itself must resolve that path for its own file operations. The exception is an omitted optional `path` input with no `default`, which resolves to the empty string.
   103	- `validate`, when present, is a Rust `regex`-crate pattern applied to the string representation of the resolved scalar value and anchored to the entire rendered value.
